<HL>
   Iraq Can Survive Winter
   Of Embargoes, Study Says
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A Congressional Research Service study says
Iraq can survive the winter's embargoes by shifting to a
vegetarian diet, rationing food and smuggling in whatever it
can.
   The assessment came as Baghdad announced its intentions to
cut off food to non-Arabs and extend rationing to rice,
flour, sugar, tea and cooking oil. Bread has been rationed
since Sept. 1.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a report to Congress, an agriculture-policy analyst for
the Library of Congress's research arm said Iraq's chances of
holding out against trade sanctions depend largely on how
quickly it turns toward subsistence farming and substitutes
domestic crops for food imports. Until its invasion of
Kuwait, Iraq imported 75% of its food, including feed grain
for egg and poultry production.
   "Locally grown potatoes can be substituted for imported
rice," the analyst, Susan Epstein, said. "Locally grown dates
can be pressed to obtain a sweetener to replace imported
sugar, and locally grown barley can replace imported wheat
for bread." In addition, the Iraqis can switch to beans and
lentils as a protein alternative to meat, she said.
   Shortages, Ms. Epstein said, will be offset somewhat by a
fall harvest of vegetables and the slaughter of livestock as
farmers run out of feed grain. Iraqi farmers will begin
planting their barley and wheat crops next month, for harvest
in May and June. In the meantime, rationing of dwindling
wheat and rice stockpiles must be strictly enforced.
   Over the long term, Ms. Epstein said, efforts to increase
production will be limited by the lack of seed and
farm-equipment parts and the exodus of foreign technicians
who had repaired irrigation rigs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0145
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0145.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   U.S. Newsprint Usage
   Dropped 1% in August
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
RAW AND FINISHED PAPER PRODUCTS (PAP)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The American Newspaper Publishers
Association estimated newsprint consumption by all U.S. users
at 992,824 metric tons in August, a decrease of less than 1%
from a year earlier.
   For the first eight months of the year, the industry group
estimated that consumption rose 1% to 8,034,531 metric tons.
A metric ton is equal to about 2,204.62 pounds.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The association said U.S. daily newspapers used 735,722
metric tons of newsprint in August, slightly lower than
742,642 metric tons used a year earlier. Daily newspapers'
consumption in the first eight months was little changed at
5,980,211 metric tons.
   Newsprint inventories of newspapers in the association's
statistical sample averaged a 41-day supply in August,
compared with a 40-day supply a year earlier. The association
said stocks of North American mills were down 17%.
   The association said Canadian newsprint mills operated at
90% of rated capacity in August and at 94% in the first eight
months. U.S. mills operated at 98.7% in August and at 97.1%
in the year-to-date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
