<HL>
   International:
   Critic Says Japan
   Is Too Subservient
   To U.S. in Gulf
   ----
   By Urban C. Lehner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST JAPAN
</CO>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- If Shintaro Ishihara, Japan's best known
nationalist, were prime minister Japan's Persian Gulf policy
would be very different indeed.
   Mr. Ishihara dismisses Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu as "an
innocent boy" and calls Japan's management of the current
crisis "childish." He favors a posture that's both more
reliant on the United Nations, on the one hand, but
potentially more willing to commit Japanese military force to
the region, on the other. While completely unsympathetic with
Saddam Hussein and his aggression on Kuwait, Mr. Ishihara is
very sympathetic with Arab nationalism.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "They {the Arabs} still have a sense of colonial
domination by white people," Mr. Ishihara said in an
interview. "Japan can sympathize with them. We too are
colored in a way. Japanese have a different mentality from
white people."
   Mr. Ishihara, a Liberal Democratic Party member of
parliament and co-author of the controversial book "The Japan
That Can Say No," doesn't necessarily speak for anyone but
himself.
   But he is one of Japan's most popular politicians. Many
Japanese admire his outspoken views, even though they
wouldn't dare say such radical things themselves. In
particular, many Japanese agree with Mr. Ishihara that Japan
is too subservient to the U.S.
   "I'm not saying Japan should say `no' to the U.S. 100%" in
the Gulf situation, he says. But he would like Japan's Gulf
policy to be "a bit aloof" from the U.S.'s. The countries
whose stances he most admires include the Soviet Union, which
is broadly supportive of the multinational forces in the Gulf
but wants a stronger role for the United Nations.
   Mr. Ishihara believes the U.S. was too hasty in
dispatching forces to the Gulf. He would have advised making
more use of the United Nations first. Now that U.S. forces
are present, he says, the U.S. runs enormous risks. If Saddam
Hussein emerges from the situation with any part of his
initial aims achieved, the most radical elements in the
region will be inspired to try to topple all moderate Arab
regimes friendly to Washington. So if war ensues, Mr.
Ishihara muses, the U.S. had better not stop at recovering
Kuwait; it had better "go all the way to Baghdad."
   By totally subscribing to the U.S. line, Mr. Ishihara
believes, Japan gives away one of its most important "cards,"
the chance to play a mediating role in the crisis. He says
73% of Iraq's foreign aid -- but none of its armaments --
came from Japan, which could have given Japan both leverage
and a strong moral platform for playing a mediating role.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Destroying the Banks to Save Them
   ----
   By Peter Wallison
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   There's a simple way to describe Washington's current
response to financial weakness in the banking industry:
panic. Fearful that banks may be going the way of the S&amp;Ls,
policymakers are uncritically advancing solutions that will
bring about the result they are hoping to avert.
   In July, several officials called for higher capital
requirements for banks -- a goal that was widely endorsed in
Congress and the press. In August, the FDIC proposed raising
deposit insurance premiums for banks by the maximum allowable
amount -- to almost 20 cents on every $100 of deposits --
again to resounding applause. In September, the Comptroller
General of the United States, in testimony before the Senate
Banking committee, reported that the FDIC's bank insurance
fund was near depletion and recommended that the FDIC be
permitted to raise deposit insurance rates without limit in
order to restore the integrity of the fund. This idea was
endorsed even by the Treasury Department and legislation to
bring it about was passed by the House and introduced in the
Senate by Donald Riegle, the Chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   How would banks that are required to raise their capital
be expected to do so? There are basically three ways: sell
shares, retain earnings or sell off assets (and shed
corresponding liabilities). The success of the first two
obviously depends on the ability of management to earn
profits. The sale of shares is heavily disfavored because it
dilutes the ownership of current shareholders -- but it is
unlikely to be a viable option in any case because (as the
S&amp;Ls have discovered) there is no market for the shares of a
depository institution that is only marginally profitable.
   Increasing profitability, on the other hand, means
increasing risk, since the more profitable loans and
investments are those that have the greatest inherent risk.
Selling assets and shedding liabilities is a viable course,
but in practical terms it also means increasing risk because
the market is interested only in buying the banks' least
risky assets. Thus, it is not necessarily true that raising
capital standards for banks will leave them stronger; in
fact, if banks must strive to meet higher capital
requirements they may weaken themselves by increasing the
relative riskiness of their portfolios.
   Then there is the issue of deposit insurance premiums.
Obviously, an increase in these premiums will reduce the
profitability of banks, making it harder for them to increase
capital or to maintain the capital levels they already have.
And although a deposit insurance premium of almost 20 cents
on every $100 of deposits does not sound very large, it is
important to remember that a reasonably well-managed U.S.
bank earns about $1 on every $100 of assets, with money
center banks generally below this level. Since banks fund
about 75% of their assets with deposits, a deposit insurance
premium even at the current level represents about 15% of
pretax earnings and is thus a significant amount. An increase
in this obligation will obviously further reduce the earnings
of banks and cause them -- if they are to remain profitable
-- to take on greater risk even if they don't have to
increase their capital.
   Thus, not only is there a contradiction between higher
deposit insurance premiums and requiring banks to increase
their capital, but both steps -- together and separately --
will weaken the financial condition of banks by causing them
to take on more portfolio risk. Why, then, have both ideas --
together and separately -- been so widely applauded in
Washington?
   The reason seems to be that Washington policymakers have
mistakenly assumed that the best protection for the taxpayers
is the health of the deposit insurance funds. This is
completely wrong. As clearly shown by the S&amp;L debacle, the
best protection for the taxpayers is not the size of the
deposit insurance funds; it is the health of the institutions
these funds insure.
   Once a substantial portion of a whole industry begins to
slip toward insolvency, the deposit insurance funds have no
meaning. The liability of the taxpayers for the S&amp;L
industry's massive losses goes far beyond the size of the
insurance fund that once guaranteed the deposits in S&amp;Ls,
even when the insurance fund was at its healthiest. For this
reason, the current debate about the optimum size of the bank
insurance fund is a sideshow -- except to the extent that the
policies chosen to rescue the fund contribute further to the
weakness of the industry the fund insures.
   To some extent, Washington is confused by its own
rhetoric. Deposit insurance was presented as insurance, in
much the same way and for much the same reason that Social
Security was. But deposit insurance is insurance in name
only. The size of the deposit insurance fund bears no
relationship to the risks it is intended to cover. The
premiums paid by insureds bear no relationship to the risks
they impose on the fund, and are not intended to -- and do
not -- affect the riskiness of their behavior.
   It is important to make this distinction, because if
deposit insurance were in fact insurance then the proper
response to a decline in the size of the deposit insurance
fund would be higher premiums on banks -- since higher
premiums in a true insurance scheme would discourage the
behavior insured against. But deposit insurance premiums are
not insurance premiums; they are a tax on the banking
industry, levied for the privilege of receiving federal
government and ultimately taxpayer backing for certain
liabilities. If there were ever any doubt about this
proposition, it was removed by the S&amp;L bailout, in which the
presence or absence of an insurance fund was largely
irrelevant. Depositors were bailed out by the taxpayers; the
FSLIC fund served at most as a small deduction from the
taxpayers' total bill.
   Looked at in this way, it becomes far less clear that an
increase in deposit insurance premiums is the appropriate
response to a decline in the size of the deposit insurance
fund. Clearly, there is growing financial weakness in the
banking industry. This weakness has already caused a
substantial decline in the size of the deposit insurance fund
administered by the FDIC. The relevant question, however, is
not how to shore up the fund but how to address the banking
industry's weakness. It cannot seriously be contended that
banking or any other industry will be strengthened when
higher taxes are levied on it.
   When Congress was considering the S&amp;L bailout legislation
last year, it was warned that the S&amp;L industry could not
survive increased capital requirements, increased deposit
insurance premiums, reduced investment opportunities and
lower earnings from its investment in the Home Loan Bank
System. Although this would seem fairly obvious to most
people, the purpose of the legislation was not the survival
of the industry but the survival of the legislators. A year
later, we can only hope that policymakers will take a longer
term view.
   ---
   Mr. Wallison, White House and Treasury department counsel
during the Reagan administration, is an attorney in
Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0112
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Unlisted Shares Continue Slide on Oil;
   Oracle Victimized by Apparent Trickery
   ----
   By Dave Pettit
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Over-the-counter stocks slipped on oil again
yesterday.
   Crude oil prices increased nearly 90 cents a barrel,
sending stock prices lower again as investors continued to
grapple with the inflationary impact of higher oil prices.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The losses left the Nasdaq Composite Index at its lowest
level since January 1988. The index closed at 341.19, down
8.84 or 2.5%.
   New York Stock Exchange issues faired somewhat better; the
Big Board composite index lost 2.16, or 1.3%, and the Dow
Jones Industrial Average shed 32.17, or 1.3%.
   While oil price movements largely dictated the stock
markets' direction, traders say other issues also continue to
influence the market. Rumors about the military standoff in
the Persian Gulf and the ongoing federal budget talks in
Washington also affected stocks, traders say.
   "The tone of the market is definitely bearish right now
and there's really nothing that's going to turn that around,"
says Len Hefter, managing director of Jefferies &amp; Co.'s OTC
desk in Dallas.
   "Until something definitive starts to happen in the Middle
East, it's going to be the same thing -- a lot of
nervousness," Mr. Hefter says.
   Nasdaq decliners overwhelmed advancers, 1,486 to 561.
Volume climbed to 153.3 million shares, up sharply from
Wednesday's 118.7 million shares.
   Traders agree that even if a budget accord is reached, it
will be only a short-term positive for stocks with the Middle
East crisis continuing to loom.
   "There are just too many negatives, too many rumors and
stories. You just can't operate intelligently in a market
when that's going on," says Robert Antolini, head of OTC
trading at Donaldson Lukfin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
   Oracle fell 5/8 to 5 5/8 in heavy trading yesterday after
gyrating wildly on two apparently fabricated documents
alleging Oracle is the target of a takeover bid. Oracle, a
highflying supplier of database software that has fallen on
hard times, declined to comment on the documents.
   One of the documents, which appeared to be an internal
memo from Prudential-Bache Securities, declared that "an
offshore concern is about to file its intention to acquire
Oracle as early as next week." But an official at
Prudential-Bache insisted the document was fraudulent.
   The other document, purporting to be a press release from
Hitachi Ltd., stated it was Hitachi's intention to acquire
five million of Oracle's shares. But the document contained
numerous errors and misstated Hitachi's formal name.
   On Tuesday, Oracle announced a quarterly loss that was
one-third larger than the company predicted three weeks ago.
The loss, the company's first ever, comes on the heels of
disclosures of accounting "glitches" and financial
restatements at the company. The string of disclosures has
torpedoed the company's stock, which peaked late last year at
more than $28. Oracle was the day's most active issue, as
4.77 million shares were traded.
   Other active stocks included Intel, down 3/4 to 32 on 4.2
million shares; Conner Peripherals, down 1 3/8 to 16 1/8 on
2.7 million-shares; and Sun Microsystems, down 2 to 25 3/4 on
1.6 million shares.
   NovaCare Inc. lost 1/2 to 14 5/8 as 3.2 million of its
common shares came to market at $15 each. A total of 2.2
million NovaCare shares changed hands on the day.
   Dain Bosworth equity trader Dennis Murray says that some
of the few sectors of the market that have maintained their
favored status are finally falling out of grace. "We are
seeing more and more darling stocks being taken out and
getting shot," he says.
   Among these fallen angels are health care and
biotechnology stocks, he says. In those areas yesterday,
Amgen lost 2 3/8 to 46 1/4, St. Jude Medical lost 3/4 to 26
3/4, U.S. HealthCare shed 1 3/4 to 17 7/8 and Biomet dropped
1/4 to 27 3/4.
   Pop Radio's shares lost more than a third of their value,
shedding 5 1/8 to 10 after Heritage Media suggested that the
firms' merger pact may be in jeopardy.
   Heritage Media, in a Securities and Exchange Commission
filing, said it doesn't expect all conditions of the merger
to be satisified by an Oct. 31 deadline, at which time both
companies can back out of the transaction. Heritage said it
hasn't yet decided whether to proceed with the merger after
the deadline.
   Meanwhile, Nike shares fell 3 3/4 to 60 3/4. A Nike
spokesman said the firm doesn't have any news pending. He
indicated that Nike is "very comfortable" with analysts'
estimates in the range of $7.50 to $8.25 a share for the
fiscal year ending in May 1991. Nike earned $6.42 a share in
fiscal 1990.
   Action Auto Rental gained 3/4 to 2 5/8 after the company
announced plans to buy back up to three million shares.
   Software Toolworks fell 1 1/4 to 6 1/4 after Piper Jaffray
&amp; Hopwood analyst Bob Kleiber lowered his earnings estimates
for the company's 1991 and 1992 fiscal years.
   Mr. Kleiber cut his forecast for the fiscal year ending
March 31, 1991, to a range of between $1.20 and $1.40 a share
and lowered his fiscal 1992 estimate to between $1.85 to
$2.15.
   Network General shed 1 7/8 to 4 1/4 after disclosing that
it expects second quarter net income to be below its first
quarter level of 13 cents a share, as adjusted for a
two-for-one stock split. Additionally, the company said that
shipments of its "WatchMaster" product have been deferred.
   Network General's disclosures prompted Alex. Brown &amp; Sons
Inc. analyst, John Rohal, to downgrade his investment rating
on the stock to "hold" from "buy" and to trim his earnings
estimate for the firm.
   OTC financial stocks continued to founder, including
insurer Cincinnati Financial, which fell 1/4 to 73 after
trading as low as 66 3/4. While a company spokesman Wednesday
said the firm knew of no reason to account for the fall,
earlier this week analysts blamed the drop on short sellers.
The stock fell 4 7/8 Wednesday.
   Among other insurance firms, Ohio Casualty dropped 1 3/4
to 29 1/4, St. Paul Cos. lost 3 to 48, Safeco dropped 1 to 26
7/8 and Provident Life shed 3/4 to 16 3/4.
   The banking sector was hit with more negative news as New
York Stock Exchange-traded Bank of Boston joined the ranks of
institutions projecting losses and reducing their quarterly
dividend payouts.
   Midlantic lost 1/2 to 7 3/8, BayBanks dropped 1 1/4 to 12
1/4, Michigan National lost 3/4 to 22 and State Street Boston
fell 7/8 to 29 1/8.
   U.S. Trust Corp. fell 3/4 to 28 3/4 on top of its 3/8 loss
Wednesday. The company said Wednesday that $16.2 million in
special charges in the third quarter would result in a loss
of about $7 million, or 77 cents a share, for the period.
Last year, U.S. Trust earned $10.5 million, or $1.05, in the
third quarter.
</TEXT>
