<HL>
   SE Banken's Ramfors Thrives on Change
   ----
   By Stephen D. Moore
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   S.SEB U.SBG
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   STOCKHOLM -- Bo Ramfors says he spent a decade as a senior
executive at Scandinavia's biggest bank "moving very
comfortably in the shadow of big men."
   So much so that the affable 54-year-old banker was an
unknown quantity when management upheaval catapulted him last
year into the chief executive officer's job at Sweden's
Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken. Many analysts viewed Mr.
Ramfors as an interim choice to head the bank. After all, it
was well known among Stockholm's tight-knit financial
fraternity that he had reserved the right to retire from the
bank at age 55.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But Mr. Ramfors has surprised just about everybody, and
right now retirement is the last thing on his mind. Seizing
the reins with obvious relish, he pushed through a sweeping
management shake-up, scrapping SE Banken's unwieldy
collective management and taking over executive power
himself.
   With assets of 360 billion Swedish kronor ($62.4 billion),
SE Banken is one of the world's 100 biggest banks. For three
consecutive years, beginning in 1986, it was the world's most
profitable, according to annual rankings prepared by London
rating agency IBCA Banking Analysis Ltd.
   However, profitability has slipped during the past 18
months, and Mr. Ramfors frets that times are about to get
even tougher. So he's ordered a cost-cutting drive aimed at
slashing overhead in the bank's domestic operations between
8% and 12% during the next 18 months.
   Meanwhile, Mr. Ramfors is stepping up the pace of SE
Banken's international expansion. Three months ago, the bank
agreed to pay #153 million ($286.1 million) for the 78% it
didn't already own of Scandinavian Bank Group PLC of London.
SE Banken's biggest acquisition in years, it also was an
important step toward broadening the operational base of
Enskilda Securities, SE Banken's London-based merchant
banking unit and the spearhead for Mr. Ramfors's
international ambitions.
   For all that activity, Mr. Ramfors has kept quiet about
what some consider his most impressive accomplishment so far
-- healing a longtime breach between SE Banken's dominant
shareholders. Relations have been sour between the bank's
biggest owners -- Sweden's Wallenberg group and the corporate
alliance of automaker AB Volvo and contracting group Skanska
AB -- since a bitter power struggle in the early 1980s.
   The big owners have become increasingly worried about the
bank's sluggish profitability -- and appalled by the
plummeting price of SE Banken shares. In a series of secret
meetings this summer, Mr. Ramfors and his major shareholders
huddled to hone the management restructuring plan. That
cooperation smoothed acceptance of the plan from the bank's
full 43-member board, as well as the quartet of managing
directors, who saw much of their previous power usurped.
   Staunch support from the big owners promises to be a trump
card as Mr. Ramfors struggles to squeeze better performance
from the bank.
   SE Banken's management woes turned acute last autumn.
Jacob Palmstierna, an urbane aristocrat hand-picked to run
the bank, resigned under pressure of allegations of tax
evasion after serving as chief executive officer less than
six months. (A Stockholm appeals court acquitted Mr.
Palmstierna of tax evasion charges earlier this month. Mr.
Palmstierna isn't expected to return to the bank.)
   The loss of Mr. Palmstierna was a double blow. He had been
expected to run the bank through the 1990s. More importantly,
his departure upset the balance among the four managing
directors who made up the bank's executive committee.
   The committee wielded power collectively. The system, and
veto powers granted each managing director, dated from the
1970 merger that created SE Banken. The system prevented
either merger partner from steamrolling the other.
   Unfortunately, the consensus system proved virtually
impossible to dismantle. One reason was the bank's ponderous
board structure: 36 directors and deputies elected by
shareholders plus seven more state appointees. The bottleneck
choked decision-making.
   The atmosphere of crisis stirred by Mr. Palmstierna's
forced departure helped pave the way for change at the bank,
SE Banken insiders say. "But Mr. Ramfors surprised everyone
by really bulldozing this through. He went to the big owners
with an ultimatum -- make changes or he'd leave," says a
senior SE Banken official.
   The owners couldn't afford to lose another chief executive
officer so soon after Mr. Palmstierna's departure. Moreover,
they shared Mr. Ramfors's concern about the bank's prospects.
   Operating profit at the parent bank climbed a modest 6%
during this year's first four months after remaining flat
last year at about 3.6 billion Swedish kronor. Reflecting the
problems, SE Banken's Series A shares -- the most traded
class of equity -- have plunged 33% over the past 12 months.
   "SE Banken just hasn't been professionally run," says a
senior official at a rival Stockholm bank. "If you look at
their client base, by far the strongest in Sweden, it's
obvious that if they were well managed, annual profit would
be at least 50% higher."
   Mr. Ramfors is concerned that the bank's hefty profit in
recent years was swelled by unique, windfall factors.
Sweeping market deregulation enabled Swedish banks to post
huge bond trading profits, he says. In addition, abolition of
longtime quotas on bank lending ushered in a burst of
unprecedented credit expansion, and favorable interest rate
movements swelled margins on banks' lending.
   The coming decade, he insists, will be a different story.
SE Banken still earns virtually all its profit from
traditional commercial banking inside Sweden. Yet Mr. Ramfors
expects Sweden's economy to reap only marginal benefits from
the European Community's 1992 single-market plan. Meanwhile,
political constraints and Sweden's huge public sector will
continue to damp economic growth at home.
   Credit expansion, he adds, probably will slow to about the
same rate as Swedish inflation from its heady 20% to 30%
annual growth rates in recent years. And the current
segregation of banks and insurers will cease, sharpening
competition for insurance and other consumer-oriented
financial services, which Mr. Ramfors expects to be virtually
the only source of growth for domestic operations.
   "That sets the '90s for us," he says. "We won't see growth
in the economy, and we won't see growth in banks."
   Operations outside Sweden will have to pick up the slack.
Though wary of fierce competition in many segments of
international banking, Mr. Ramfors says SE Banken "will
follow our customers abroad in the profitable segments where
we have competence." He cites two potential areas in
particular -- fund management and corporate finance,
including cross-border mergers and acquisitions. Enskilda
Securities has gradually carved out profitable international
niches in both fields.
   "We know there's a hell of a battle underway in Europe,"
Mr. Ramfors says. And at least for the time being, he rules
out interest in a major acquisition within the EC. "But since
we've got a first-class customer base, which not too many
banks have, we'd be stupid not to try. As long as it doesn't
take too much capital, why can't Swedes do it? That's my
approach."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0101.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Machine-Tool
   Firms to Post
   Poor 3rd Period
   ---
   Weak Orders in Second Half
   Of 1989, Early 1990 Led
   To Depressed Shipments
   ----
   By Ralph E. Winter
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6B
</SO>
<CO>
   CMZ MMO GIDL CTCO HURC
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
FACTORY EQUIPMENT (FAC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Machine-tool producers will report dismal third quarter
profits. Shipments were depressed because of weak orders in
1989's second half and the first few months of 1990.
   Machine tools are large, complex machines that shape metal
parts, and there often is a lead time of several months to a
year between receipt of an order and shipment of the machine.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The industry also is beset by intensely competitive
pricing. There's excess capacity in the U.S. machine-tool
industry, and foreign producers are shipping in machines from
abroad and adding plant capacity in the U.S.
   Nonetheless, "the tone at the recent machine tool show in
Chicago was quite upbeat," said Eli S. Lustgarten, machinery
analyst with PaineWebber. "Industry orders for 1990 will be
up 4% to 6% from last year, and they'll rise another 5% to
10% next year," he said. That's far from a boom, he added,
but it should produce improved industry profits in 1991.
   For one thing, automotive companies are expected to place
some long-deferred orders for equipment to produce new
engines and other basic parts for 1993 and 1994 model cars.
"The stumbling blocks that delayed the orders are falling,"
Mr. Lustgarten said, and auto makers don't have much more
time, if they want to avoid slipping another year behind the
Japanese in car design.
   Order deferral by car and truck makers was a major reason
for the machine tool order drop that began in the spring of
1989.
   The declining value of the dollar is one of this year's
few plus factors. Machine-tool exports in 1990's first half
rose 17% from a year earlier, and may set a record for the
full year, exceeding the $1 billion of 1981, according to the
NMTBA -- the Association for Manufacturing Technology, a
McLean, Va., trade group.
   The machine-tool industry isn't energy-intensive, and
won't be hurt directly by higher oil prices. However, orders
would drop if rising oil prices and uncertainty about the
threat of war in the Middle East bring on a recession in the
U.S. and slow economic activity abroad.
   On the other hand, machine-tool companies are receiving
more orders from makers of oilfield drilling equipment, pumps
and valves as oil prices rise and demand for natural gas
increases.
   In addition, higher gasoline prices may increase auto
company purchases of equipment to make new 16-valve,
four-cylinder engines and four-speed automatic transmissions.
The auto industry has been undecided about whether to make
more six-cylinder engines for larger, higher performance
cars, or to tool up for fuel-efficient models.
   Government fuel-economy regulations pressure the companies
to emphasize economy, but consumer demand was tilting
strongly toward performance. Higher gasoline prices could
resolve the issue in favor of economy.
   Longer term, if oil prices remain high, U.S. industry will
renew efforts to conserve energy, such as operating more
fuel-efficient trucks, airplanes and heavy machinery. That
would boost orders for machine tools in 1991 and beyond.
   In the third quarter, negatives outweighed the positives.
Cincinnati Milacron Inc. said it's too early to make a
precise third-quarter earnings estimate, but that profit
probably will be in the ballpark of the disappointing 12
cents a share earned in the second quarter. In 1989's third
period, when Milacron was feeling the brunt of restructuring
problems, profit from continuing operations was $3.3 million,
or 13 cents a share, on sales of $233.8 million. Net income
was $2.5 million, or 10 cents a share.
   Milacron's profit in recent quarters has suffered from
reduced shipments of some of its higher margin products, such
as plastics-injection molding machines. Also, the company is
shipping some machines that carry inadequate profit margins,
reflecting competitive pricing. Milacron has become more
selective about the business it accepts, a spokesman said,
but still has some low-margin business on the books.
   Monarch Machine Tool Co., Sidney, Ohio, also is having a
disappointing third quarter, mainly because of reduced orders
during the spring and summer, said Robert J. Siewert,
president. The producer of lathes, machining centers and
equipment for processing coils of sheet metal will be
profitable for the quarter, he said, but it's too early to
say whether net will exceed the modest $271,942, or seven
cents a share, Monarch earned a year ago on $24 million
revenue.
   Monarch began the year expecting sharply higher profit in
1990, but second and third-quarter earnings fell far below
expectations, Mr. Siewert said. The company's British lathe
operation had lower shipments at the same time that domestic
machine-tool business was in a slump. Orders have improved
recently, he said, and the fourth quarter will be the best
earnings period for the year.
   Giddings &amp; Lewis Inc., Fond du Lac, Wis., is faring better
than most other machine-tool builders this year; it expects
to approximate last year's third-quarter net of $4.8 million,
or 46 cents a share. "Our bookings have held up, and we have
a good backlog," said Richard Kleinfeldt, vice president and
chief financial officer. He doesn't quarrel with analyst
estimates that the company will earn $1.80 to $1.85 a share
for the year, up from $17.1 million, or $1.65 a share, in
1989, when sales were $233.1 million.
   Cross &amp; Trecker Corp. concedes that it won't realize a
previously announced goal of turning profitable in fiscal
1990, which ends Sunday. The Bloomfield Hills, Mich., company
expects to report a loss for the fourth quarter larger than
the year-ago quarter's loss of $1 million, or eight cents a
share. However, fiscal 1990's loss will be far smaller than
the loss of $46.5 million, or $3.76 a share, for all of
fiscal 1989, which included a restructuring charge of $21.3
million.
   Reduced orders at the KT-Swasey unit, which produces
machining centers and lathes, and at the Sheffield measuring
machine unit, are major factors in the expected
fourth-quarter loss, Cross &amp; Trecker said. Sheffield is
profitable, but will earn less than a year ago.
   In addition, Cross has had difficulty in arranging
financing for a large Soviet order. Last March, Cross
received Soviet orders totaling $63 million for machinery to
equip a Soviet auto plant. West German banks agreed to
finance the $28 million portion of the order placed with the
Cross plant in West Germany. However, U.S. banks won't
finance the $35 million part that was to be produced in
Michigan, delaying the program, Cross said. U.S. banks are
skittish about whether the Soviets would make the repayments.
   The company accounts for large contracts on a percentage
of completion basis, and had expected to book as much as
$700,000 of operating profit from the Soviet order in the
Sept. 30 quarter. Cross may transfer production to another
country to obtain financing, possibly reopening a Canadian
facility.
   The order slowdown hit Hurco Cos., Indianapolis, just as
the producer of machining centers and electronic controls was
increasing spending on new-product development and its
marketing and customer-service organization. This year, Hurco
introduced a new generation of machine-tool controls and will
market five new machine tools, said Michael K. Campbell,
senior vice president and chief financial officer.
   Hurco's profit in the third quarter, ended July 31,
plunged to $1.1 million, or 19 cents a share, from $2.2
million, or 45 cents a share, a year earlier. The company
expects net for the Oct. 31 fourth quarter to approximate the
third period's, which would be less than half the $2.9
million, or 51 cents a share, earned in the year-ago quarter.
   However, Hurco could exceed a fiscal 1990 earnings
estimate of $1.20 a share if sales in the final weeks of the
year keep pace with a recent increase in customer inquiries,
Mr. Campbell said.
   For fiscal 1989, Hurco earned a record $8.2 million, or
$1.70 a share, on sales of $93.7 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Psychosis and Civil Rights
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
</IN>
<LP>
   In what was heralded as a landmark step, Governor Mario
Cuomo and New York City Mayor David N. Dinkins recently
announced a new plan to aid the mentally ill homeless.
Nowadays when politicians announce progressive new programs
for the mentally ill, sensible people start to worry -- with
cause.
   The track record of such programs, beginning with the
catastrophic one that "liberated" the mentally ill by
removing them from institutions that cared for them, is not
reassuring. Thanks to this grand remedy conceived in the name
of progress in the late 1960s, a huge army of severely sick
and dependent people now make their home in the streets. How
they got there is no mystery.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Public-interest attorneys and civil libertarians, rushing
to the barricades of what they saw as a great new
civil-rights movement, mounted a war of lawsuits against
state mental hospitals all through the '70s. Such advocates
pressed demands for patient liberation, and for rights
including a mentally ill person's right to refuse treatment.
The result of these efforts was the phenomenon known as
deinstitutionalization.
   The mental hospitals emptied out while the nation's bus
terminals, parks and subway gratings filled up with hordes of
the afflicted now free to wander where they would, untended.
An army of psychotic and delusional people had been released
to a freedom that was, in effect, their abandonment.
   The architects of deinstitutionalization now concede that
it has been a calamitous failure but argue that this is only
because of the government's failure to provide supporting
funds for outpatient clinics and group homes. It is an
argument that fails to address the core problem of the
mentally ill.
   That problem, simply put, is that the mentally ill require
treatment which they are incapable of seeking for themselves.
All the funds and group homes in the world are of no avail so
long as residents can wander as they please and refuse
medication. A new book titled "Madness In the Street" by Rael
Jean Isaac and Virginia C. Armat argues that when the
diseased organ is the brain, afflicted individuals can't be
expected to make reasoned decisions regarding treatment. As
author Isaac told us, "at least half the mentally ill don't
think there is anything wrong with them."
   Governor Cuomo and Mayor Dinkins now have introduced a
housing program for the mentally ill, based on the model of
residences run by Franciscan priests. They are models well
worth emulating. A visitor to their residences discovers
clean, cheery homes closely supervised by caretaker priests
and medical attendants who make it a priority to see that the
residents take their anti-psychotic drugs. The priests remove
and try to hospitalize anyone who refuses to take the
stablizing medication.
   The question posed by the Cuomo-Dinkins plan is whether
state-run bureaucracies hamstrung by worries about lawsuits
can or will emulate the successful voluntary efforts of the
Franciscans. Those who favor publicly administered support
for such problems must answer the question of whether
government has become so encumbered -- by politicians,
lawyers, pressure groups, TV cameras -- that it simply can no
longer perform these tasks effectively.
   The legal tangle produced by the patients' rights
advocates is such that it is now nearly impossible to commit
patients involuntarily, without offering the most compelling
and extreme proof that they pose a danger to themselves or
others. State hospitals now can hardly be persuaded even to
take people who wish to be committed, unless they can prove
they are dangerous to themselves or others. Mental illness is
apparently the only disease requiring the sufferer to reach
the worst stage before he is considered eligible for
treatment. There is something wrong with this situation.
   The chaos in the homeless shelters and terminals where the
mentally ill gather testifies to the results. Most of the
mentally ill are not violence prone, but the segment that is
poses dangers not to be ignored. Arrest rates for violent
crimes are now consistently higher for the mentally ill than
for that of the general population. This can hardly be
surprising in a wandering population no longer in a position
where they can be given the anti-psychotic medication needed
to help and stabilize them.
   It is clearly time to start reordering priorities and to
begin rethinking the complex of recently litigated legal
rights whose primary effect is to prevent gravely ill people
from receiving treatment. It's time to start hospitalizing
people who need it, and to recognize that creating a right
that allows extremely disturbed people to refuse treatment
amounts to the right to live in degradation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
