<HL>
   Business Brief -- Colonial Realty Corp.:
   Bankruptcy-Court Petition
   Is Converted to Chapter 11
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   Colonial Realty Corp., the embattled West Hartford, Conn.,
real estate syndicator, got a reprieve yesterday when a
petition for involuntary bankruptcy-court liquidation of the
company was converted into a Chapter 11 reorganization.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Robert Krechevsky approved a
request by Colonial's lawyers to convert the Chapter 7
petition, which was filed on Sept. 14 by six banks. The
banks, including a unit of Bank of New England Corp. and
People's Bank of Bridgeport, did not oppose the conversion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Colonial, which is closely held, has marketed limited
partnerships on real estate once valued at more than $1
billion.
   "Obviously, this is in the best interests of the investors
and of the company," said Colonial spokesman Tom Drohan.
   John Nolan, a Hartford lawyer who represents one of the
banks, said that a creditors commitee had been formed, which
would seek court approval to hire Coopers &amp; Lybrand to
examine the company's books.
</TEXT>
