900928-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Management:
   Lure of Legacies Perks Up Directors
   ----
   By Richard Gibson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Charity, it's said, begins at home. But for a growing
number of corporate directors, it is being bankrolled in the
board room.
   Some of the nation's largest corporations are quietly
giving their directors the ability to leave handsome nest
eggs to the charity or charities of their choice -- at no
cost to the directors.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It's the new million-dollar board perquisite. There's one
big catch: The gift isn't given until the director dies.
Payable to the designated charities upon death, the gift is
financed by insurance policies taken out by the company on
the director's life.
   Typically, the policies will mean an eventual tax-free
windfall of between $500,000 and $2 million for the board
member's alma mater, favorite disease-fighting effort or
other worthy cause. The average legacy is $1 million.
   "This allows a person to have an eternal impact, to really
leave something for generations to come," says E. Webb
Bassick IV, an executive compensation partner at Hewitt &amp;
Associates, management consultants based in Chicago.
   Companies say the perk helps them to lure the most
desirable directors and keep them on board. Attracting and
retaining directors isn't an easy task these days, say
executive recruiters. Mere cash doesn't cut it any longer, as
increased responsibilities and liability concerns prompt many
prospective directors to reject board invitations and many
incumbents to leave sooner. A recent Korn/Ferry International
survey finds that nearly half of the major companies it
polled expect at least one director to leave this year.
   "If you're having difficulty getting directors to sit on
your board, this could make the difference," says Mr.
Bassick.
   While the beneficiaries of the legacies will have to wait
for their money, the companies can take the cost of premiums
as an expense. More significantly, when the director does
die, the policy payoff can be included in the company's
charitable gift tax deduction since the money actually flows
from the insurer through the company and on to the intended
beneficiary.
   Still, many companies are reluctant to publicize the perk.
While promoters of the million-dollar legacies say more than
two dozen major companies offer it to their directors,
General Electric Co., PPG Industries Inc. and Westinghouse
Electric Corp., among others, don't disclose it. "We did not
deem this to be compensation," a Westinghouse spokesman says.
   "Corporations find there's a lot of focus on the magnitude
of director benefits, and they'd just like to avoid the issue
if they could," says Louis R. Richey, a vice president of
Ayco Corp., an American Express Co. unit that markets the
legacy perk.
   Some companies also worry that shareholders will think
such plans enrich directors, or look on any eleemosynary
activity as a misuse of corporate assets.
   But other companies see charitable giving as a public
relations plus. Waste Management Inc.'s proxy statement views
the perk as part of the company's "overall program to promote
charitable giving as a means to enhance the quality of life
in the many communities" in which it operates.
   Because the perk doesn't compensate the individual --
although a grateful college may send him or her some choice
game tickets -- there is no requirement that it be disclosed
as a board benefit. Lawyers also say disclosure can be ducked
since, during the director's lifetime, his or her legacy
isn't irrevocable. The corporation could decide to
countermand the bequest wishes.
   So far that hasn't happened. Insurers say no director
covered by such a policy has yet died.
   Alexander Trowbridge, former president of the National
Association of Manufacturers who sits on Waste Management's
board, says his intended beneficiary is Phillips Academy in
Andover, Mass., where he chairs the planned-giving committee.
Mr. Trowbridge, who calls the legacy benefit "a brilliant
idea," says he has urged the school's leadership to recommend
it to other directors-alumni.
   H. Brewster Atwater Jr., General Mills Inc.'s chairman and
chief executive officer, is on two boards with the perk --
his own and GE's. And while he says he intends to leave a
"good portion to education and a good portion to cultural
activities," Mr. Atwater hasn't notified the prospective
recipients "because I might find I may be more interested in
something else five years from now."
   Legacy policies for directors are so new that only a
handful of insurers offer them. Thus, some companies find it
cheaper to bid out the coverage themselves.
   Similar insurance has been available for well-to-do
individuals. But until recently, such policies haven't been
used as corporate benefits.
   Initially the program isn't cheap: annual premiums can
cost upwards of $25,000 per director. "You've really got to
dig behind the numbers and see if you agree with all the
assumptions," says Hewitt's Mr. Bassick, noting that
dividend, tax and interest rates should be considered. "As
with any life insurance product, you have to look at it in
the same decision process as building a new factory: Should
we be using the funds in another way?"
   A company should also ask what the buying power of today's
dollars will be decades from now. "We're looking at a face
value of $1.5 million and saying, `Boy, what a lasting gift.'
But in 30 years it may not buy the tribute we think of
today," notes Mr. Bassick.
   Health is always an important factor in buying life
insurance. But some companies are getting around that by
pairing older directors who may be poor risks with younger,
healthier board members. Under such "survivorship" policies,
the insurer doesn't pay out either director's benefits until
both are dead. That could complicate the selection of
would-be beneficiaries.
   "There's a lot of flexibility in policies. Premiums depend
on how long a company wants to pay out," says Amy Kalkbrenner
of Connecticut Mutual Life Insurance Co., a Hartford, Conn.,
insurer specializing in the "survivorship" policies.
   But this perk isn't for everyone. Smaller companies may
find the cost too great, or alternative uses of the money
preferable. And some large companies -- among them apparel
maker Hartmarx Corp. and pharmaceuticals giant Merck &amp; Co. --
say they've studied the legacy perk program but passed, for
various reasons.
   Some companies let directors pick the beneficiary. But PPG
asks directors to use their legacies to support education,
partly to foster a smarter work force for the future.
American Express and Union Pacific Corp. also have a say.
They split the proceeds between designated recipients and
their in-house charitable foundations.
   A few companies that offer the plan to directors are
expanding it to include senior executives. Usually in those
cases, though, employees share the insurance cost with the
company, and their coverage may be considerably less than
that afforded directors. At Bell Atlantic Corp., only outside
directors with at least five years' service are eligible for
the perk. Raymond W. Smith, the company's chairman, says
directors may decide to increase the $500,000 maximum legacy
in lieu of more cash.
   The legacy idea wins plaudits from many in the financial
planning and executive-compensation fields. "I don't think
that in the decade just past we were ready for this,"
Hewitt's Mr. Bassick says. "We were too cash-driven. Today,
charitable giving fits."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0064
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0064.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   L.A. Gear's Profit
   In Third Quarter
   Declined by 35%
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LA
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- L.A. Gear Inc.'s fiscal third-quarter
profit fell 35% to $14.3 million, or 71 cents a share,
disappointing most analysts.
   The athletic-shoe maker said earlier this month it would
report lower profit in the quarter ended Aug. 31. Sales
climbed 40% to $300.3 million from $215 million. Net income
in the year-ago quarter was $22 million, or $1.21 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   L.A. Gear said it expects fourth-quarter and full fiscal
year profit to fall from year-ago levels, in part because of
higher advertising expenses. Analysts had already been
predicting lower net so the forecast didn't come as any
surprise.
   Gross margins in the third quarter improved to 35.6% from
34.85%, less than some analysts expected. Faster sales growth
overseas than in the U.S., where sales produce higher
margins, restricted the gain, L.A. Gear said. In the quarter,
domestic sales grew only about 10% to $220 million.
   Advertising and promotional expense of $26.5 million in
the quarter included $9.3 million of expenses that had been
deferred from earlier in the year. L.A. Gear said it didn't
have any deferred advertising expense as of Aug. 31.
   To bolster market share, the company announced it is
boosting fourth-quarter advertising by about $2.5 million to
roughly $17 million. L.A. Gear's share has been increasing
since last year when it stood at about 10% of the $5 billion
athletic footwear market.
   Despite a difficult retail environment, "we continue to be
optimistic with regard to our potential and are enthusiastic
about our new products," said Robert Greenberg, chairman and
chief executive officer. The bigger advertising budget "is
intended to give us the greatest possible platform from which
to market our exciting new styles."
   In particular, L.A. Gear said it is launching a multimedia
campaign featuring San Francisco 49ers' quarterback Joe
Montana, to sell the company's Street Hiker shoe. L.A. Gear
didn't mention its new line advertised by singer Michael
Jackson. Some retailers have indicated that the shoe, which
costs up to $80 in some stores, is a flop.
   The shoe isn't a large percentage of projected sales or
inventory, said Kevin Ventrudo, chief financial officer.
"International sales have been good." A television commercial
with Mr. Jackson has helped the company's brand awareness
independent of the shoe's sales, he said.
   L.A. Gear fell 87.5 cents to $11.25 in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading yesterday. The profit report was
issued after the close of trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0063
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0063.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Figgie Chief's
   Son Is Named
   Vice Chairman
   ----
   By Ralph E. Winter
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   FIGIA WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Harry E. Figgie Jr., chairman and chief executive officer
of Figgie International Inc., brought his son, Harry E.
Figgie III, into the company as vice chairman, with the
assignment of speeding the adoption of new technology.
   The Figgies said during a joint interview that there isn't
any understanding that the move places Dr. Figgie, who is 37
years old, in position to succeed his 66-year-old father as
chief of the diversified company the senior Mr. Figgie
founded 26 years ago.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   There has been speculation since Dr. Figgie joined the
Figgie International board in 1985 that the senior Mr. Figgie
would keep the top job in the family. However, when asked
whether he plans to retire at any given date, Mr. Figgie
responded, "Hell, no. This is an exciting time. Things I've
waited my whole career to see are happening now."
   The senior Mr. Figgie said the Willoughby, Ohio, company
has "a five-year window of opportunity to integrate new
technology" into its divisions. "There's been a technological
revolution," in machining, welding, assembly, product design
and other functions, he said, and in some industries the
company that successfully employs the new methods first "will
own the business."
   Figgie, which expects 1990 sales of nearly $1.4 billion,
supplies fire-protection and security systems and services;
produces sporting goods, electronics systems and industrial
products, and is involved in real estate development and
other activities.
   Dr. Figgie, who is an orthopedic surgeon as well as a
manufacturing executive, will phase out of his medical
practice over the next 18 to 36 months to head technology and
strategic planning at Figgie. He will be a member of a new
three-member office of the chairman, which will include the
senior Mr. Figgie and Vincent A. Chiarucci, 60, the company's
president and chief operating officer.
   The senior Mr. Figgie said those divisions serving the
construction industry have experienced a rapid drop in orders
during the current quarter. The company is cutting employment
and speeding up the previously planned consolidation of
certain units to adjust to the lower business volume, he
said. He declined to make an earnings forecast.
   Dr. Figgie has headed Clark-Reliance Co., a family-owned
manufacturer of valves, controls and instrumentation since
1975, when he was entering Case Western University's School
of Medicine. In addition to his medical degree, Dr. Figgie
has undergraduate degrees in bio-medical engineering and
accounting and a master's degree in factory automation. He
currently is an assistant clinical professor of medicine at
Case and has a surgical practice specializing in artificial
joint replacement.
   Dr. Figgie said he had "reached a fork in the road" where
he had to concentrate exclusively on business or medicine. He
said he chose business because he finds the application of
new manufacturing technologies exciting and challenging.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0062
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
