<HL>
   Business Brief -- Fiat S.p.A.:
   Car Maker's Pretax Profit
   Fell Almost 13% in 1st Half
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FIA
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   Consolidated pretax profit at Fiat S.p.A. fell almost 13%
in the first half, reflecting increased competition in its
home market and weakening demand for new cars in Europe
generally.
   The Italian car maker forecast a tough second half, saying
the Gulf crisis, higher inflation and the country's
continuing budgetary problems were likely to hurt business.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated pretax profit fell to 2.45 trillion lire
($2.09 billion) in the first half from 2.81 trillion lire in
the same period of 1989, while consolidated net revenue rose
to 30.31 trillion lire from 27.11 trillion.
   Fiat's market share in Italy fell to 54% in the first six
months from 58% a year earlier. Fiat has encountered strong
competition on its own turf from Ford Motor Co., which has
doubled its market share in Italy to 7% this year following a
strong marketing campaign for its new-style Fiesta model,
which competes head-on with Fiat's top-selling Uno.
   In the wider European market, Fiat's sales rose to
1,080,000 vehicles in the first half from 1,040,000 vehicles
a year earlier, but its market share slipped to 15% from
15.5%.
   Another factor in the fall in the group's profitability
was heavy losses by Fiat's Brazilian subsidiaries, totaling
more than 300 billion lire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0057
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0057.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Au Printemps S.A.:
   French Retail Firm Returns
   To Profit in the First Half
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A
</SO>
<CO>
   F.PRI
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
</IN>
<LP>
   Au Printemps S.A. said it had consolidated net profit of
57 million French francs ($10.9 million) for the first half
of 1990, compared with a year-earlier loss of 50 million
francs.
   The French retailing group said that part of the
improvement reflected its decision to no longer include in
its results its 25% stake in the distribution group
Euromarche S.A. During the first half of 1989, Euromarche cut
about 30 million francs off Printemps' earnings.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Printemps said earnings were also helped by the use of
proceeds from 1989 asset sales -- totaling about 800 million
francs -- to pay down its debt and reduce costs.
   Revenue climbed 2% to 13.96 billion francs from 13.66
billion. Pretax profit from current operations surged to 192
million francs from 92 million.
   Printemps wouldn't forecast full-year earnings because of
the unknown impact of the Persian Gulf crisis on demand
during the second half. However, it said it expects a
significant improvement in its current operating profit for
the year.
   For 1989, Printemps had consolidated net profit of 524
million francs on revenue of 28.5 billion francs.
</TEXT>
