<HL>
   BCE, Nynex Join
   In Bid for Mexico's
   Phone Company
   ----
   By G. Pierre Goad
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   BCE NYN LATAM TFONY T.B
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   MONTREAL -- BCE Inc. and Nynex Corp. are joining with a
Mexican financial concern to bid for control of Telefonos de
Mexico.
   The joint venture is the first group to announce it will
make an offer for a 20.4% TelMex equity stake held by the
Mexican government. The 20.4% block represents just over half
of TelMex's full-voting shares. Three other groups are
expected to join the bidding.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Henri Roy, a BCE senior vice president, said that based on
the current stock price TelMex is worth about $7 billion,
giving the 20.4% stake an indicated value of about $1.4
billion.
   Mr. Roy wouldn't say if the joint venture expects to offer
a premium for the control block. The Mexican government
currently holds about 56% of TelMex while the remainder is
publicly held.
   BCE and Nynex will each own about 25% of the venture and
Casa de Bolsa Inverlat Associates, a Mexican financial
concern, will own at least 50.1%. Mr. Roy said the partners
are still working on the details of their bid, which must
include a detailed operating plan for TelMex.
   Under rules established by the Mexican government, groups
making bids must be at least 50.1%-owned by Mexican investors
and must include at least one foreign telephone company. The
bidding process is only open to concerns approved by the
government. Four Mexican groups (a fifth dropped out) and 12
foreign telephone concerns have been accepted as possible
bidders by the government, Mr. Roy said.
   The bidding deadline is Nov. 15 and the government expects
to make a decision by the end of the year, Mr. Roy said.
   The winning bidder faces a massive job modernizing TelMex,
Mr. Roy said. But for BCE and Nynex the Mexican telephone
monopoly also represents a "tremendous opportunity." He said
there is the potential for "double-digit annual growth" at
TelMex. He said the telephone monopoly only has about five
million telephone lines in operation now and the Mexican
economy could support twice that number.
   Mr. Roy said the Mexican government has guaranteed TelMex
a monoply on basic phone service until 1996. He said the
telephone monopoly is profitable and has annual revenue of
about $5 billion.
   BCE, parent of Bell Canada, is a Montreal-based holding
company. Nynex is the New York-based Baby Bell. Inverlat is
based in Mexico City. The joint venture's announcement was
made after the market closed yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0038
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0038.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Ing. C. Olivetti &amp; Co.:
   Consolidated Pretax Profit
   For the First Half Fell 41%
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   I.OLV
</CO>
<IN>
OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Ing. C. Olivetti &amp; Co. of Italy, an office automation
equipment maker, reported that first-half consolidated pretax
profit fell 41% to 60.9 billion lire ($51.9 million) from
102.6 billion lire a year earlier, continuing a 3 1/2-year
earnings slide.
   Operating profit fell 35% to 102.1 billion lire from 156.4
billion lire.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Revenue rose 5.8% to 4.167 trillion lire from 3.938
trillion lire.
   Carlo De Benedetti, chairman and the controlling
shareholder, blamed the earnings drop on tough market
conditions, a continuing squeeze in profit margins and an
unfavorable exchange rate for the lira. But the company
claimed it fared much better than most of its European and
U.S. competitors, and predicted it will continue to outpace
other computer makers for the rest of the year, though it
didn't give a specific earnings forecast.
</TEXT>
