<HL>
   Business Brief -- Teradata Corp.:
   Computer Concern Expects
   Fiscal First-Quarter Loss
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TDAT
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Teradata Corp. said it sees a fiscal first-quarter loss of
between 40 cents a share and 50 cents a share on
lower-than-expected revenue of about $50 million.
   In the year-ago quarter, the Los Angeles computer systems
concern earned $2.4 million, or 17 cents a share, on revenue
of $43 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Teradata said it is "taking a number of actions to
significantly reduce operating expense levels in anticipation
of lower-than-expected revenue growth" for the fiscal year
ending June 30. Some of these actions will result in a
"modest" first-quarter charge, the company said.
   "We intend to reduce our operating expenses . . .
sufficiently to provide year-over-year earnings growth" in
fiscal year 1991, Teradata said. This year, the company had
net income of $16.3 million, or $1.15 a share.
   Teradata attributed the revenue shortfall to slow sales in
Germany and Europe, including postponement of purchases by a
large European customer. The company said orders had been
disappointing from bank customers, particularly in the
Northeast.
</TEXT>
