<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUDGET NEGOTIATORS neared a compromise that would limit
tax deductions for the rich and lower the levy on capital
gains less than Bush had sought. The package would also tax
more of the Social Security benefits paid to middle-income
and wealthy recipients, and raise the gas oline tax by eight
cents a gallon.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   T. Boone Pickens agreed to disgorge $2.3 million of profit
from his 1988 sale of Homestake Mining stock, as part of a
settlement of SEC charges that he misled investors.
   ---
   MCA and Matsushita plan to meet next week to begin
negotiating the Japanese electronics giant's possible
acquisition of the entertainment firm.
   ---
   The FDIC predicted its bank insurance fund will lose $3
billion this year, up from the $2 billion projected by the
agency earlier this month.
   ---
   Bank of Boston cut its dividend and said it will add about
$175 million to its loan-loss reserves and trim its staff by
1,500, or 8%, of its employees.
                                                                                                       

   Banking stocks sank for the fifth session in a row amid
fears that the industry's exposure to problem loans is worse
than bankers believe.
   ---
   Oil prices rose, briefly surpassing $40 a barrel, despite
an initial drop in reaction to Bush's decision to tap
reserves. The International Energy Agency is expected to urge
its 21 member countries to be ready to dip into their
stockpiles, but it won't yet call for a coordinated release.
   ---
   Stocks fell and bonds rose as recession fears intensified.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 32.17 points lower
after fluctuating wildly in heavy trading. The 30-year
Treasury bond jumped one point.
   ---
   Neil Bush conceded he stood to benefit from a line of
credit he sought from Silverado S&amp;L for a partner.
   ---
   Milken's sentencing was delayed as a judge ordered an
unusual hearing on additional crimes that the prosecution
contend he committed.
   ---
   Union Carbide plans to buy as much as 14% of its stock,
cut its debt and reap about $300 million from as set sales.
The moves are aimed at bolstering the firm's shares, which
rose 62.5 cents to $14.875 on the news.
   ---
   GM and Ford are idling five plants that make light trucks
in a sign of weakness in that market segment.
   ---
   Unisys decided to omit its common-stock dividend. The
company's already battered stock sank 23%.
   ---
   Mexico is worried that Canadian participation in
U.S.-Mexican talks on a free-trade agreement could delay or
jeopardize the accord.
   ---
   Campbell Soup's only director to have pushed publicly for
a sale of the company quit the board abruptly, dimming
prospects for a takeover.
   ---
   Tokyo's property-related stocks have plummeted 55% so far
this year, indicating to some analysts that Japan's land
prices are about to plunge.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 182,690,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2427.48, off 32.17; transportation 828.03, off 18.49;
utilities 198.69, off 1.13.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3352.75, up
33.38.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.66, up 0.14; spot
index 129.38, off 0.73.
   Dollar: 138.00 yen, up 1.16; 1.5612 marks, off 0.0038.
</TEXT>
