<HL>
   Law:
   Hearing Will Delay Milken Sentencing
   ----
   By Laurie P. Cohen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
SECURITIES (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A federal judge delayed the sentencing of
Michael Milken, scheduled for Monday, and ordered an unusual
hearing to consider additional crimes the government has
alleged Mr. Milken committed, but to which he hasn't pleaded
guilty.
   U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood said she would hold a
two-week hearing to air the government's allegations against
the former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. junk-bond king. The
hearing will likely be held next month. Judge Wood said she
planned to give both prosecutors and defense lawyers 20 hours
each to present arguments and cross-examine witnesses.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As previously reported, prosecutors had sought such a
hearing -- over the strenuous objections of Mr. Milken's
lawyers -- and have notified lawyers for witnesses who aided
the government in its case against Mr. Milken that these
witnesses may be called to testify.
   Among the witnesses the government has indicated it may
call are Ivan F. Boesky, the convicted former Wall Street
stock speculator, and David Solomon, a former money manager.
Prosecutors have also notified former Drexel employees that
they may be called.
   Yesterday, Arthur Liman, Mr. Milken's lead lawyer, opposed
such a hearing, saying it "will prolong the agony" of Mr.
Milken's family. Mr. Liman said he would talk to prosecutors
during the weekend to see if a hearing could be avoided.
   Prosecutors sought the hearing because they want Judge
Wood to consider the full force of their case against Mr.
Milken when she sentences him. Mr. Milken pleaded guilty last
April to six felony counts relating to securities fraud and
faces a maximum jail term of 28 years.
   The government has urged Judge Wood to sentence Mr. Milken
to "substantial" jail time and has painted the 44-year-old
Mr. Milken as a white-collar criminal of major proportions.
In a sentencing memorandum made public earlier this week, the
government unleashed a barrage of additional alleged crimes
that it believes Mr. Milken committed. The alleged crimes
include insider trading and illegal payoffs to certain money
managers and other favored clients.
   Mr. Milken's attorneys have urged Judge Wood to view Mr.
Milken's crimes as aberrations in an otherwise exemplary life
and to sentence him to perform fulltime community service.
His lawyers have accused the government of presenting
evidence of offenses that Mr. Milken has "never acknowledged
and has never committed."
   In calling for the extraordinary hearing, Judge Wood said
that the court may take into account unadmitted conduct in
issuing a sentence. "Considering unadmitted conduct gives the
court a sense of a defendant's character," Judge Wood said.
   She said that to avoid a lengthy hearing on all of the
government's allegations, she would limit the time that the
government could spend presenting its case. She said she
expected the government to concentrate on less than a dozen
of the transactions it has alleged were illegal, but to which
Mr. Milken hasn't admitted guilt.
   A judge is not obligated to take the government's
additional allegations into consideration when deciding on an
appropriate sentence. But if Judge Wood decides she wishes to
consider the additional evidence in meting out a sentence,
Mr. Milken is entitled to defend himself at a hearing.
   A similar battle over sentencing took place earlier this
year in the case against Robert Freeman, the former head of
arbitrage at Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. who pleaded guilty to a
single charge of insider trading. In that case, the judge
said that in issuing a sentence, he wouldn't consider any
crimes other than that to which Mr. Freeman pleaded guilty.
The government alleged that Mr. Freeman committed some 20
other crimes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900928-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900928-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   GM Cuts Discounts
   On Certain Models
   In 1990, 1991 Lines
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   GM
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp. is raising prices on some
1990 and 1991 models by cutting the cash discounts offered to
buyers.
   In effect, the No. 1 auto maker is joining Ford Motor Co.
in a gamble that efforts to boost revenue in a slumping
market won't cost market share in the competition against
Japanese auto makers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   GM didn't raise prices as much as Ford, which earlier this
week eliminated cash-to-customer rebates on leftover 1990
models and sharply scaled back the discounts on many
high-volume 1991 models. Unlike Ford, GM left cash discounts
on most 1990 models. However, rebates on some high-volume
1990 and 1991 Chevrolet models will be substantially less
than they were just a few days ago.
   For example, someone who bought a 1990 Chevrolet Corsica
Monday got a $1,000 cash rebate. But buying a 1990 Corsica
today will mean only $500 off the sticker price, in effect a
$500 price boost.
   GM is raising the prices on 1991 Corsicas, too, by cutting
the cash rebate to $500 from $750. Similarly, the rebate on
1990 Chevrolet Lumina mid-sized sedans was cut to $500 from
as much as $1,500.
   "Certainly we watch what other people do," a Chevrolet
spokesman said. The decision to cut back on rebates in part
reflects lower stocks of unsold cars on GM dealer lots, he
said.
   GM isn't raising prices on every model. Some weak-selling
models will come with even bigger discounts. The rebate on
certain 1990 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme Coupes rose to $2,500
from $2,000. The discount on other Cutlass Supremes will
remain at $2,000.
   GM's bid to raise prices on high-volume lines reflects
growing pessimism about the strength of the U.S. auto market.
GM and Ford, by raising prices, are signaling that they're
resigned to a period of weak sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
